\description{
Single entry point for fitting a Bayesian hierarchical model. \code{tulpa()}
parses the formula, builds the model matrices, selects an inference backend
through the tier/mode system (see \code{\link[=inference_mode_info]{inference_mode_info()}}), assembles the
arguments that backend needs, and dispatches.

The fit conditions on the random-effect standard deviations \code{sigma_re} (and,
for non-Gaussian dispersion, \code{phi}): both the Laplace (Tier 2) and the
sampler (Tier 1) paths target the posterior given these. Integrating over the
hyperparameters is the role of the nested-Laplace / EM layer.
}
\section{Coverage}{

\itemize{
\item \strong{No random effects} and \strong{random intercepts} (\code{(1 | g)}) are supported on
the design path (\code{mode = "laplace"}) and the sampler path (\code{mode = "mala"},
\code{"pathfinder"}, \code{"imh_laplace"}, and the ModelData kernels \code{"hmc"} / \code{"sghmc"}
/ \code{"sgld"} / \code{"mclmc"} / \code{"smc"} / \code{"vi"} / \code{"ess"}).
\item \strong{Random slopes} are supported on the Laplace (Tier 2) path: there is no
scalar \code{sigma_re} to condition on, so the RE covariance \code{Sigma} is integrated
rather than fixed. This covers correlated terms (\code{(1 + x | g)}, a full
\code{Sigma}), uncorrelated terms (\code{(1 + x || g)}, a diagonal \code{Sigma}), and
several terms together (\code{(1 + x | g) + (1 | h)}) -- each term becomes a
covariance block, and any accompanying \code{(1 | g)} term is integrated as a 1x1
block (nothing is silently conditioned at \code{sigma_re = 1}). \code{mode = "laplace"}
routes to the nested-Laplace \code{Sigma} integrator (\code{\link[=tulpa_re_cov_nested]{tulpa_re_cov_nested()}},
CCD design + PC/LKJ prior); \code{control$re_cov = "gibbs"} switches to the exact
Metropolis-within-Gibbs debias (\code{\link[=tulpa_re_cov_gibbs]{tulpa_re_cov_gibbs()}}), and
\code{control$re_cov = "aghq"} keeps the nested integrator but replaces the
inner joint-Laplace marginal with adaptive Gauss-Hermite quadrature
(\code{control$n_quad}, default 9 there; see \code{n_quad} in
\code{\link[=tulpa_re_cov_nested]{tulpa_re_cov_nested()}}). Both also run on the
sampler path (\code{mode = "mala"} / \code{"pathfinder"}).
\item \code{mode = "gibbs"} (Polya-Gamma) fits a single random-intercept model for
\code{family = "binomial"} or \code{"neg_binomial_2"}, and \strong{samples} the RE sd
rather than conditioning on \code{sigma_re}; tune it via
\code{re_prior$prior_sigma_scale} and a mean-zero \code{beta_prior}.
\item \strong{Latent prior blocks} (\code{latent(tgmrf(...))}) route to the nested-Laplace
path (Tier 2), which integrates over the block hyperparameters. \code{mode = "auto"} and \code{"structured"} select it automatically when latent blocks are
